'''Sebastian Vettel''' ({{IPA|de|zeˈbasti̯a(ː)n ˈfɛtl̩|-|De-Sebastian Vettel.ogg}}; born 3 July 1987) is a German former [[racing driver]] who competed in [[Formula One]] from {{F1|2007}} to {{F1|2022}}. Vettel won four [[Formula One World Drivers' Championship titles]], which he won consecutively from {{F1|2010}} to {{F1|2013}} with [[Red Bull Racing|Red Bull]], and remains the [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions#Youngest Drivers' Champion|youngest-ever World Drivers' Champion]]; he won 53 [[Formula One Grands Prix|Grands Prix]] across 16 seasons.

Born and raised in [[Heppenheim]], Vettel began competitive [[kart racing]] aged eight. After a successful karting career—culminating in his victory at the [[KF3|junior]] [[Karting European Championship|European Championship]] in 2001—Vettel graduated to [[formula racing|junior formulae]]. He started his career in [[Formula BMW#Germany & Europe|Formula BMW ADAC]], dominating the championship in [[2004 Formula BMW ADAC season|2004]] with 18 wins from 20 races. Vettel then progressed to the [[Formula 3 Euro Series]] in [[2005 Formula 3 Euro Series|2005]], taking several victories and finishing runner-up to [[Paul di Resta]] the [[2005 Formula 3 Euro Series|following season]]. A [[test driver]] for [[BMW Sauber]] since {{F1|2006}}, Vettel made his Formula One debut at the [[2007 United States Grand Prix]]. Vettel replaced [[Scott Speed]] at [[Toro Rosso]] after the {{F1GP|2007|European}} for the remainder of the {{F1|2007}} season, as part of the [[Red Bull Junior Team]]. Retaining his seat for {{F1|2008}}, Vettel achieved his maiden [[pole position]] and victory at the {{F1GP|2008|Italian}} to become the [[List of Formula One driver records#Youngest winners|then-youngest driver to win a Formula One Grand Prix]]. Vettel was promoted to parent team [[Red Bull Racing|Red Bull]] in {{F1|2009}}, taking several wins as he finished runner-up to [[Jenson Button]] in the [[World Drivers' Championship]].

After winning the title-deciding {{F1GP|2010|Abu Dhabi}} in {{F1|2010}}, Vettel became the [[List of Formula One driver records#Youngest World Drivers' Championship - first-time winners|youngest-ever Formula One World Drivers' Champion]], aged 23. He won his second and third championships in {{F1|2011}} and {{F1|2012}}, dominating the former and winning the latter amidst a close title battle with [[Fernando Alonso]]. Vettel set several records in {{F1|2013}}, winning 13 Grands Prix—including a [[List of Formula One driver records#Most consecutive wins|then-record]] nine consecutive victories—to claim his fourth consecutive title with Red Bull. After a winless {{F1|2014}} campaign, Vettel signed for [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]], replacing Alonso to partner [[Kimi Räikkönen]]; he took several wins in his [[2015 Formula One World Championship|debut season]], finishing third in the standings. Following another winless season in {{F1|2016}}, Vettel emerged as the closest challenger to [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]] and [[Lewis Hamilton]], finishing runner-up in {{F1|2017}} and {{F1|2018}} after achieving several victories across both campaigns. Partnered by [[Charles Leclerc]] for {{F1|2019}}, Vettel took the final win of his career at the {{F1GP|2019|Singapore}} before leaving Ferrari at the end of the {{F1|2020}} season. Vettel joined the recently established [[Aston Martin in Formula One|Aston Martin]] in {{F1|2021}}, where he scored his final podium finish at the {{F1GP|2021|Azerbaijan}}.

Vettel retired at the end of the {{F1|2022}} season, having achieved the fourth-most [[List of Formula One Grand Prix winners#By driver|wins]] (53), fourth-most [[List of Formula One polesitters|pole positions]] (57), fifth-most [[List of Formula One drivers who set a fastest lap|fastest laps]] (38), and fourth-most [[List of Formula One driver records#Total podium finishes|podium finishes]] (122) in Formula One. He won the [[Race of Champions]] in [[2015 Race of Champions|2015]], further winning the [[Race of Champions#Winners|Nations' Cup]] six consecutive times from [[2007 Race of Champions|2007]] to [[2012 Race of Champions|2012]], representing Germany alongside [[Michael Schumacher]]. Vettel is also a prominent [[environmental activism|environmental]] and [[climate activist]]; since 2023, he has been co-owner of the Germany [[SailGP]] Team.

